## Provider Configuration — Firebase

Follow these steps **once** to provision the credentials referenced in `.env.local`.

### Step 1 — Create or select a Firebase project

1. Go to [Firebase Console](https://console.firebase.google.com/).
2. Click **Add project** → enter a project name → accept Google Analytics defaults (or skip) → **Create project**.
3. Once provisioned, click the gear icon → **Project settings**.

### Step 2 — Register a Web App and get client config

1. In **Project settings** → **General** → **Your apps**, click the **`</>` (Web)** icon.
2. Give it a nickname (e.g., `web`), **uncheck** "Also set up Firebase Hosting" (unless you plan to host there), click **Register app**.
3. Copy the `firebaseConfig` values shown — these become the `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_*` env vars below:
   - `apiKey` → `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY`
   - `authDomain` → `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN` (format: `<project-id>.firebaseapp.com`)
   - `projectId` → `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID`
   - `storageBucket` → `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET`
   - `messagingSenderId` → `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID`
   - `appId` → `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID`

### Step 3 — Generate a Service Account key (Admin SDK)

1. **Project settings** → **Service accounts** tab.
2. Click **Generate new private key** → confirm in the modal → a JSON file downloads.
3. Open the JSON and copy these three fields into `.env.local`:
   - `project_id` → `FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID`
   - `client_email` → `FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL`
   - `private_key` → `FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY` (paste the **entire** value including the `BEGIN PRIVATE KEY` header line and the `\n` escapes)

> **DO NOT commit the JSON file.** Delete it after copying. Your `.gitignore` already blocks `*.json` service-account keys, but verify before staging.

### Step 4 — Enable sign-in methods

1. Left nav → **Authentication** → **Get started** (if first time).
2. **Sign-in method** tab → enable:
   - **Email/Password** → toggle **Enable** → **Save**.
<!-- IF oauth=google -->
   - **Google** → toggle **Enable** → set support email → **Save**.
<!-- /IF -->

### Step 5 — Add authorized domains

1. **Authentication** → **Settings** → **Authorized domains**.
2. Verify `localhost` is listed (default). Add your production domain when deploying.

<!-- IF oauth=google -->
### Step 6 — Configure Google OAuth (5-step checklist)

`signInWithPopup` will fail with **400 Bad Request** if any of these steps are missed.
The full 5-step OAuth checklist (with screenshots of every screen) lives in the plugin reference:

→ See [`references/05-firebase-auth-guide.md` § Google OAuth Setup Checklist](https://github.com/MangalaHQ/shipwithai-plugins/blob/main/plugins/auth/skills/auth-setup/references/05-firebase-auth-guide.md#critical-google-oauth-setup-checklist)

Quick summary:

1. **Firebase Console** → Authentication → Sign-in method → enable Google (Step 4 above).
2. **Google Cloud Console** → APIs & Services → Credentials → find the OAuth client created by Firebase.
3. Add to **Authorized JavaScript origins** (no paths):
   - `http://localhost`
   - `http://localhost:3000`
   - `https://<PROJECT>.firebaseapp.com`
   - `https://your-production-domain.com`
4. Add to **Authorized redirect URIs** (must include `/__/auth/handler`):
   - `https://<PROJECT>.firebaseapp.com/__/auth/handler`
5. **OAuth consent screen** → if status is **Testing**, add your email under **Test users**.

Replace `<PROJECT>` with your Firebase project ID.

> ⚠️ Common mistake: do **not** add `/api/auth/callback/google` — that's the Auth.js convention, **not** Firebase's. Firebase always uses `/__/auth/handler`.
<!-- /IF -->

